ğŸ§ Essential Linux Commands for Cyber Security Beginners

This list covers the most important Linux commands every beginner should know, especially for penetration testing and CTFs.

ğŸ“ File & Directory Management
pwd        # Show current directory
ls         # List files
ls -la     # List all files (including hidden) with details
cd dir     # Change directory
cd ..      # Go one directory back
mkdir dir  # Create directory
rmdir dir  # Remove empty directory
rm file    # Delete file
rm -rf dir # Delete directory recursively (âš ï¸ dangerous)
cp src dst # Copy file
mv src dst # Move/rename file
touch file # Create empty file
file name  # Identify file type
stat file  # Detailed file info
tree       # Show directory tree

ğŸ” File Viewing & Reading
cat file        # Print file content
less file       # View file (scrollable)
more file       # Simple viewer
head file       # Show first 10 lines
head -n 20 file # First 20 lines
tail file       # Last 10 lines
tail -f log     # Follow live log
nl file         # Show file with line numbers

ğŸ” Searching & Filtering
grep "text" file          # Search text in file
grep -i "text" file       # Case-insensitive search
grep -r "text" dir        # Recursive search
find / -name file.txt     # Find file by name
find / -type f            # Find all files
locate filename           # Fast file search
which python              # Show command path
whereis python            # Locate binary/source


ğŸ’¡ Cyber tip: grep + find are used constantly in CTFs.

ğŸ§® Permissions & Ownership
chmod +x file        # Make executable
chmod 755 file       # Set permissions
chown user file      # Change owner
chown user:grp file  # Change owner & group
ls -l                # View permissions
umask                # Show default permissions

ğŸ‘¤ User & System Info
whoami      # Current user
id          # User identity info
hostname    # System hostname
uname -a    # Kernel/system info
uptime      # System uptime
history     # Command history
clear       # Clear terminal

ğŸ“Š Process Management
ps aux            # Show running processes
top               # Live process monitor
htop              # Better process viewer
kill PID          # Kill process
kill -9 PID       # Force kill
pkill name        # Kill by process name
bg                # Resume in background
fg                # Bring to foreground
jobs              # Show background jobs

ğŸŒ Networking Commands (VERY IMPORTANT)
ifconfig          # Network interfaces (old)
ip a              # Show IP addresses
ip route          # Show routing table
netstat -tulnp    # Listening ports (old)
ss -tulnp         # Modern netstat
ping target       # Test connectivity
traceroute host   # Trace network path
arp -a            # Show ARP table


ğŸ”¥ Pentester essentials: ip, ss, ping.

ğŸ“¦ Package Management (Debian/Kali/Ubuntu)
sudo apt update        # Update package list
sudo apt upgrade       # Upgrade packages
sudo apt install pkg   # Install package
sudo apt remove pkg    # Remove package
dpkg -l                # List installed packages

ğŸ§µ Text Processing (Powerful in CTFs)
sort file        # Sort lines
uniq file        # Remove duplicates
wc -l file       # Count lines
cut -d: -f1 file # Cut by delimiter
tr 'a-z' 'A-Z'   # Translate chars
awk '{print $1}' # Column processing
sed 's/a/b/g'    # Stream replace


ğŸ’¡ grep + awk + sed = elite combo

ğŸ” Privilege Escalation Helpers
sudo -l              # Check sudo permissions
env                  # Show environment vars
export VAR=value     # Set environment variable
crontab -l           # View cron jobs
ps -ef --forest      # Process tree

ğŸ“‚ Archives & Compression
tar -cvf file.tar dir     # Create tar
tar -xvf file.tar         # Extract tar
tar -czvf file.tar.gz dir # Create tar.gz
tar -xzvf file.tar.gz     # Extract tar.gz
zip file.zip file         # Create zip
unzip file.zip            # Extract zip

ğŸ§  Disk & System Usage
df -h        # Disk usage
du -sh dir   # Directory size
free -h      # Memory usage
mount        # Mounted drives
lsblk        # Block devices

âš¡ Shell & Productivity Tricks
!!           # Repeat last command
!n           # Run command number n
Tab          # Auto-complete
Ctrl + C     # Stop process
Ctrl + Z     # Suspend process
Ctrl + L     # Clear screen
history | grep nmap  # Search history

